00:00:30.340 --> 00:00:35.360
So today, as people
slowly trickle in,

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:39.430
so today we're going to talk
about scattering states.

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:42.170
So we've spent a lot of time
talking about bound states,

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:44.140
states corresponding
to particles that

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:48.765
are localized in a region and
that can't get off to infinity.

00:00:48.765 --> 00:00:50.890
And in particular, when we
distinguish bound states

00:00:50.890 --> 00:00:52.431
from scattering
states, we're usually

00:00:52.431 --> 00:00:54.440
talking about
energy eigenstates.

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:56.480
They're eigenstates
that are strictly

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:58.190
localized in some region.

00:00:58.190 --> 00:01:00.380
For example in the infinite
well, all of the states

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:03.580
are strictly localized
to be inside the well.

00:01:03.580 --> 00:01:06.260
In the finite well,
as we saw last time,

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:07.780
there are a finite
number of states,

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:10.880
of energy eigenstates which
are bound inside the well.

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:12.570
But there are also
states that aren't

00:01:12.570 --> 00:01:14.320
bound inside the well,
as hopefully you'll

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:16.785
see in recitation,
and as we've discussed

00:01:16.785 --> 00:01:18.660
from qualitative structure
of wave functions,

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.580
but under the eigenfunction.

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:24.432
So why would we
particularly care?

00:01:24.432 --> 00:01:25.890
We also did the
harmonic oscillator

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.756
where everything
was nice and bound.

00:01:27.756 --> 00:01:29.130
So why would we
particularly care

00:01:29.130 --> 00:01:31.338
about states that aren't
bound for scattering states?

00:01:31.338 --> 00:01:34.932
And the obvious answer
is, I am not bound.

00:01:34.932 --> 00:01:36.640
Most things in the
world are either bound

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:37.670
or they are scattering states.

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:39.961
By scattering state just mean
things that can get away.

00:01:39.961 --> 00:01:41.250
Things that can go away.

00:01:41.250 --> 00:01:51.640
So it's easy to
under emphasize, it's

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:56.614
easy to miss the importance
of scattering experiments.

00:01:56.614 --> 00:01:58.530
It's easy to say look,
a scattering experiment

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:00.540
is where you take
some fixed target

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:02.290
and you throw
something at it and you

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:03.831
look at how things
bounce off and you

00:02:03.831 --> 00:02:05.719
try to do something
about this object

00:02:05.719 --> 00:02:06.760
by helping it bounce off.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:11.810
For example, one of the
great experiments of our day

00:02:11.810 --> 00:02:18.470
is the LEC, and it's a
gigantic ring, it's huge,

00:02:18.470 --> 00:02:21.580
at the foot of the Jura
Mountains outside of Geneva.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:24.310
And those are people and
that's the detector-- that's

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:26.050
one of the detectors,
I think, at CMS.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:28.397
And what are you doing
in this experiment?

00:02:28.397 --> 00:02:30.230
In this experiment
you're taking two protons

00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:34.770
and you're accelerating
them ridiculously fast,

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:37.501
bounded only by the speed
light, but just barely.

00:02:37.501 --> 00:02:39.750
Until they have a tremendous
amount of kinetic energy,

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:40.850
and you're colliding
them into each other.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.150
And the idea is if you
collide them into each other

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:45.390
and you watch how the
shrapnel comes flying off,

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:47.170
you can deduce
what must have been

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:48.711
going on when they
actually collided.

00:02:48.711 --> 00:02:50.850
You could do something
about the structure.

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.725
How are protons built
up out of corks.

00:02:52.725 --> 00:02:54.350
And it's easy to
think of a scattering

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:56.600
experiment as some
bizarre thing that

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:00.620
happens in particle
detectors under mountains.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:05.000
But I am currently engaged
in a scattering experiment.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.560
The scattering experiments
I'm currently engaged in

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:10.960
is light is bouncing from
light sources in the room,

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.260
off of very bits of each of you.

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:17.280
And some of it, and probably,
scatters directly into my eye.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:18.100
That is shocking.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:21.520
And through the scattering
process and deducing

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.346
what I can from the
statistics of the photons

00:03:24.346 --> 00:03:25.970
that bounce into my
eye, I could deduce

00:03:25.970 --> 00:03:28.450
that you're sitting
there and not over there,

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:29.450
which is pretty awesome.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:31.910
So we actually get
a tremendous amount

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:33.820
of the information about
the world around us

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:35.440
from scattering processes.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:37.860
These are not esoteric,
weird things that happen.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:41.290
Scattering is how you
interact with the world.

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.010
So when we do
scattering problems,

00:03:43.010 --> 00:03:45.490
it's not because we're thinking
about particle colliders.

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:46.970
It's because at the end of
the day I want to understand--

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:47.260
AUDIENCE: [SNEEZE]

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:48.885
PROFESSOR: --how
surfaces-- bless you--

00:03:48.885 --> 00:03:50.080
how surfaces reflect.

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:52.690
I want to understand why when
you look in the mirror light

00:03:52.690 --> 00:03:53.814
bounces back.

00:03:53.814 --> 00:03:55.480
I want to understand
how you see things.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:57.146
So this is a much
broader-- scattering's

00:03:57.146 --> 00:04:00.556
a much broader idea than
just the sort of legacy

00:04:00.556 --> 00:04:02.780
of how we study
particle physics.

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:05.300
Scattering is what
we do constantly.

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:07.880
And we're going to come back
to the computer in a bit.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:09.260
I'm going to close this for now.

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:09.760
Yes, good.

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:18.399
So today we're going to begin a
series of lectures in which we

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:20.760
study scattering
processes in one

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.915
dimension in various
different settings.

00:04:22.915 --> 00:04:24.290
So in particular
that means we're

00:04:24.290 --> 00:04:28.200
going to be studying
quantum particles being sent

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:32.360
in from some distance,
incident on some potential,

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:33.400
incident on some object.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.650
And we're going to ask how
likely are they to continue

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:37.733
going through, how likely
are they to bounce back.

00:04:40.730 --> 00:04:44.650
And so we're going to start
with an easy potential,

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:47.250
an easy object off which
to scatter something, which

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:49.970
is the absence of an
object, the free particle.

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:57.050
And I want to think about
how the system evolves.

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.800
So for the free particle where
we just have something of mass,

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:03.380
m, and its potential
is constant,

00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:06.030
we know how to solve the--

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:06.530
Question?

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:07.470
Yeah.

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:10.290
AUDIENCE: This may
be a little bit dumb,

00:05:10.290 --> 00:05:14.324
but given that these
states, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:19.360
PROFESSOR: Fantastic question.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:21.026
I'm going to come
back in just a second.

00:05:21.026 --> 00:05:24.110
It's a very good question.

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:27.120
So we're interested
in energy eigenstates,

00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:28.610
and we know the
energy eigenstates

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:31.275
for the free particle-- we've
written these down many times--

00:05:31.275 --> 00:05:33.150
and I'm going to write
it in the phonic form.

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:35.220
Suppose we have a free
particle in an energy

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:37.480
eigenstate with
energy e, then we

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:40.200
know it's a superposition
of clean waves,

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:44.010
e to the i kx plus
b e to minus ikx.

00:05:46.850 --> 00:05:49.820
And the normalization
is encoded in a and b,

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:51.981
but, of course, these
are normalizable states.

00:05:51.981 --> 00:05:53.480
We typically normalize
them with a 1

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:55.760
over root 2 pi for delta
function normalizability.

00:05:57.934 --> 00:06:00.350
Now, in order for this to be
a solution to the Schrodinger

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:04.100
equation, we need the
frequency or the energy e

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:08.410
is equal to h-bar squared
k squared upon 2m,

00:06:08.410 --> 00:06:10.660
and omega is this upon h-bar.

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:12.690
And knowing that,
we can immediately

00:06:12.690 --> 00:06:13.730
write down the solution.

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:14.910
Because these are
energy eigenstates,

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:17.451
we can immediately write down
the solution of the Schrodinger

00:06:17.451 --> 00:06:21.290
equation, which begins at
time t 0 in this state.

00:06:29.035 --> 00:06:31.410
So there's the solution of
the time dependent Schrodinger

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:31.909
equation.

00:06:31.909 --> 00:06:35.080
So we've now completely solved
this in full generality, which

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.510
is not so shocking since
it's a free particle.

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:42.560
But let's think about what
these two possible states are.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:44.720
What do these mean?

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:48.380
So the first thing to
say is this component

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:50.879
of our superposition
is a wave, and I'm

00:06:50.879 --> 00:06:52.420
going to call it a
right moving wave.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:54.253
And why am I calling
it a right moving wave?

00:06:54.253 --> 00:06:57.300
If you draw the real part of
this, some moment in time,

00:06:57.300 --> 00:06:59.040
it's got some crests.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:01.660
And if you draw on it a
short bit of time later,

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:03.900
I want to ask how
the wave has moved.

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.000
And, for example,
a peak in the wave

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.400
will be when kx
minus omega t is 0.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:15.780
If kx minus omega t is 0,
then kx is equal to omega t,

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:20.010
or x is equal to omega over kt.

00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:22.810
And assuming as we have
that k is positive,

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:25.290
then this says that
as time increases

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:27.420
the position increases.

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:29.580
And this one, by
exactly the same logic,

00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:33.095
x is equal to minus
omega over kt.

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:43.576
So we'll call this a right
going or right moving,

00:07:43.576 --> 00:07:47.610
and we'll call this
a left moving wave.

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:50.080
So the general solution is a
superposition, an arbitrary

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:52.270
superposition, of a left
moving and a right moving wave.

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:54.603
This should be familiar from
803 in your study of waves.

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:00.910
But as was pointed
out just a moment ago,

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:03.830
we've got a problem.

00:08:03.830 --> 00:08:06.550
Phi e or phi e is
not normalizable.

00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:13.690
And this is obvious
from if we-- let's

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:15.470
have b equal 0 for simplicity.

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.850
This is a pure phase, and the
norm squared of a pure phase

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:20.270
is 1.

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.275
And so the probability
density is constant.

00:08:22.275 --> 00:08:25.260
It's 1 from minus
infinity to infinity.

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:28.740
So the probability of finding
it at any given point is equal.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:31.215
So assuming this is on
the real line, which

00:08:31.215 --> 00:08:33.220
is what we mean by saying
it's a free particle,

00:08:33.220 --> 00:08:35.640
there's no constant you
can multiply that by

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:36.640
to make it normalizable.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:38.139
This is not a
normalizable function.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.289
So more precisely,
what we usually do

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:50.610
is we take our states phi
sub k equal 1 over root 2 pi,

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:53.160
e to the i kx.

00:08:53.160 --> 00:09:02.330
Such that phi k, phi k
prime is equal to delta.

00:09:02.330 --> 00:09:04.720
Sorry-- that's not
what I wanted to write.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:10.350
Such that-- well, fine.

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:15.970
Phi k, phi k prime is equal
to delta of k minus k prime.

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:20.932
This is as good as we can do.

00:09:20.932 --> 00:09:22.640
This is good as we
get to normalizing it.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:23.681
It's not normalized to 1.

00:09:23.681 --> 00:09:25.440
It's normalized 1k
is equal to k prime,

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:27.939
to the value of the delta
function, which is ill-defined.

00:09:27.939 --> 00:09:30.230
So we've dealt with this
before, we've talked about it.

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:31.702
So how do we deal with it?

00:09:31.702 --> 00:09:33.160
Well, we've just
learned, actually,

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:34.320
a very important thing.

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:35.940
This question,
very good question,

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:37.648
led to a very important
observation which

00:09:37.648 --> 00:09:41.470
is that can a particle, can
a quantum mechanical particle

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:45.050
be placed, meaningfully
said to be placed,

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:50.290
in an energy eigenstate
which is bound?

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:52.560
Can you put a particle
in the ground state

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:54.010
of a harmonic oscillator?

00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:54.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:55.640
PROFESSOR: Sure.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:56.140
That's fine.

00:09:56.140 --> 00:09:57.680
Can you put the
particle in the k

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:59.285
equals 7 state of
a free particle?

00:09:59.285 --> 00:10:00.397
AUDIENCE: No.

00:10:00.397 --> 00:10:00.980
PROFESSOR: No.

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:05.290
So these scattering
states, you can never

00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:08.010
truly put your particle
truly in a scattering state.

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:10.694
It's always going to be
some approximate plane wave.

00:10:10.694 --> 00:10:12.110
Scattering states
are always going

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:15.110
to be some plane
wave asymptotically.

00:10:15.110 --> 00:10:17.670
So we can't put the particles
directly in a plane wave.

00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:19.090
What can we do, however?

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:20.052
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:20.052 --> 00:10:20.760
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:23.150
We can build a wave packet.

00:10:23.150 --> 00:10:26.070
We can use these as
a basis for states,

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:28.820
which are normalizable
and reasonably localized.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:30.890
So we need to deal
with wave packets.

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:33.130
So today is going to be,
the beginning of today

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:36.034
is going to be dealing with
the evolution of a wave packet.

00:10:36.034 --> 00:10:37.700
And in particular
we'll start by looking

00:10:37.700 --> 00:10:41.210
at the evolution in time
of a well localized wave

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:43.380
packet in the
potential corresponding

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:44.900
to a free particle.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:46.650
And from that we're
going to learn already

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:48.066
some interesting
things, and we'll

00:10:48.066 --> 00:10:50.510
use that intuition for the
next several lectures as well.

00:10:50.510 --> 00:10:53.680
Questions before we get going?

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:54.195
All right.

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:58.850
So here's going to
be my first example.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:09.080
So consider for
the free particle

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:20.970
or consider a free particle
in a minimum uncertainty wave

00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:23.356
packet.

00:11:23.356 --> 00:11:25.230
So what is a minimum
uncertainty wave packet.

00:11:25.230 --> 00:11:25.680
We've talked--

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:26.190
AUDIENCE: A Gaussian.

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:27.390
PROFESSOR: A Gaussian, exactly.

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:29.556
So the minimum uncertainly
wave packet's a Gaussian.

00:11:29.556 --> 00:11:33.410
Suppose that I take my particle
and I place it at time 0,

00:11:33.410 --> 00:11:35.494
x0 in a Gaussian.

00:11:35.494 --> 00:11:37.410
I'm going to properly
normalize this Gaussian.

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.630
I hate these factors
of pi, but whatever.

00:11:39.630 --> 00:11:47.690
a root pi, e to the minus
x squared over 2a squared.

00:11:47.690 --> 00:11:52.500
So this is the wave function
at time 0, I declare.

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.400
I will just prepare the
system in this state.

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:55.816
And what I'm
interested in knowing

00:11:55.816 --> 00:11:58.180
is how does the
system evolve in time?

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:01.080
What is x psi of x and t?

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.005
So how do we solve this problem?

00:12:09.005 --> 00:12:11.380
Well, we could just plug it
into the Schrodinger equation

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:13.588
directly and just by brute
force try to crank it out.

00:12:13.588 --> 00:12:17.210
But the easier thing to do
is to use the same technique

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:19.136
we've used all the way along.

00:12:19.136 --> 00:12:20.760
We are going to take
the wave function,

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:23.080
known wave function,
known dependence on x,

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:25.900
expand it as a superposition
of energy eigenstates.

00:12:25.900 --> 00:12:29.220
Each energy eigenstates
evolved in a known fashion

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:31.460
will evolve those
energy eigenstates

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:35.180
in that superposition, and
do the sum again, re-sum it,

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:38.430
to get the evolution as
a function of position.

00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:38.930
Cool?

00:12:38.930 --> 00:12:41.610
Yeah.

