00:47:25.320 --> 00:47:29.470
But the amplitude is
exceedingly small.

00:47:29.470 --> 00:47:32.320
Instead, what we're seeing is
a huge pile up of probability

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:37.180
just before the wall, similar
to what we saw a minute ago.

00:47:37.180 --> 00:47:40.369
Except the probability
is much, much larger.

00:47:40.369 --> 00:47:41.660
And what's going to happen now?

00:47:44.873 --> 00:47:46.220
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:46.220 --> 00:47:47.220
PROFESSOR: It's leaking.

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:49.950
It's definitely leaking.

00:47:49.950 --> 00:47:54.730
But an awful lot of
the probability density

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:57.340
is not going off the cliff.

00:47:57.340 --> 00:47:59.650
This would be Thelma and
Louise cruising off the cliff

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:01.270
and then just not falling.

00:48:01.270 --> 00:48:04.186
This is a very disconcerting--
you guys get to-- yeah.

00:48:04.186 --> 00:48:06.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:06.600 --> 00:48:08.820
So see what happens,
see what happened here.

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:12.480
We've got this nice big
amplitude to go across

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:14.502
or to reflect back,
to scatter back.

00:48:14.502 --> 00:48:16.210
You really want to
fall down classically,

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:17.668
but quantum
mechanically you can't.

00:48:17.668 --> 00:48:19.160
It's impossible.

00:48:19.160 --> 00:48:22.185
So, in fact, the probability
they reflect back is 41,

00:48:22.185 --> 00:48:23.810
and we're going to
see how to calculate

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:27.051
that in the next few lectures.

00:48:27.051 --> 00:48:27.550
Yup.

00:48:27.550 --> 00:48:31.237
AUDIENCE: So the transmission
was actually really high.

00:48:31.237 --> 00:48:33.195
PROFESSOR: Transition
was reasonably high, yup.

00:48:33.195 --> 00:48:35.003
AUDIENCE: And it was
really [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:37.532 --> 00:48:38.990
PROFESSOR: It wasn't
really, sorry?

00:48:38.990 --> 00:48:41.700
AUDIENCE: It wasn't really
apparent graphically.

00:48:41.700 --> 00:48:43.200
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
it wasn't apparent.

00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:44.908
The way it was apparent
was just the fact

00:48:44.908 --> 00:48:47.380
that the amplitude that bounced
back was relatively small.

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:49.770
So what was going is any
little bit of probability that

00:48:49.770 --> 00:48:52.100
fell down had a large
effective momentum.

00:48:52.100 --> 00:48:54.690
Just ran off the
screen very rapidly.

00:48:54.690 --> 00:48:57.980
So it's hard to see that in
the simulation, it's true.

00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:02.030
We can make the-- we can
squeeze-- ah, there we go.

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:04.490
So here is-- that's
about as good

00:49:04.490 --> 00:49:07.072
as I'm going to be able to get.

00:49:07.072 --> 00:49:08.780
And it's just going
to be glacially slow.

00:49:14.229 --> 00:49:16.270
But this is just going to
be preposterously slow.

00:49:16.270 --> 00:49:18.430
I'm not even sure
there's much point

00:49:18.430 --> 00:49:20.450
in-- But you can see
what's going to happen.

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:22.410
They're going to build up, we're
going to get a little leak off,

00:49:22.410 --> 00:49:24.076
but for the most part,
the wave packet's

00:49:24.076 --> 00:49:25.285
going to go back to the left.

00:49:25.285 --> 00:49:27.575
Questions about this one
before we move on to the next?

00:49:27.575 --> 00:49:28.242
Yeah.

00:49:28.242 --> 00:49:29.158
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:32.182 --> 00:49:33.640
PROFESSOR: Are
the-- Yeah, exactly.

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:36.056
So r and t here are going to
be defined as the probability

00:49:36.056 --> 00:49:37.860
that this wave packet
gets off to infinity

00:49:37.860 --> 00:49:40.634
in either direction.

00:49:40.634 --> 00:49:43.580
AUDIENCE: What happens if you
make the energy lower than--

00:49:43.580 --> 00:49:45.121
PROFESSOR: Then you
can't have a wave

00:49:45.121 --> 00:49:47.050
packet on the left
that's moving.

00:49:47.050 --> 00:49:49.730
Because remember that
the wave packet in order

00:49:49.730 --> 00:49:53.956
to have an expected momentum
needs to be oscillating.

00:49:53.956 --> 00:49:56.580
But if the energy is lower than
the potential, its exponential.

00:49:56.580 --> 00:49:58.550
So the expectation value
for the momentum is 0.

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:00.080
So you can't have a particle
moving in from the left

00:50:00.080 --> 00:50:02.590
if it's got energy less than
the height of the barrier.

00:50:02.590 --> 00:50:04.091
Cool?

00:50:04.091 --> 00:50:04.590
Yeah.

00:50:04.590 --> 00:50:06.750
AUDIENCE: Sorry, what's
this green thing?

00:50:06.750 --> 00:50:09.208
PROFESSOR: The green thing is
the energy of the wave packet

00:50:09.208 --> 00:50:10.620
that I'm sending in.

00:50:10.620 --> 00:50:13.960
OK, so let's go to the next one.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:16.280
So this is something
we'd like to understand.

00:50:16.280 --> 00:50:17.780
The reason I'm
showing you this is I

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:21.580
want to explain this phenomena.

00:50:21.580 --> 00:50:22.830
We already did the dispersion.

00:50:22.830 --> 00:50:24.871
I want to explain this
phenomena that you reflect

00:50:24.871 --> 00:50:27.680
when going downhill, which
is perhaps surprising.

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:29.680
And I want to ask how
efficiently do reflect off

00:50:29.680 --> 00:50:31.450
any given barrier.

00:50:31.450 --> 00:50:31.950
Yeah.

00:50:31.950 --> 00:50:32.968
Question.

00:50:32.968 --> 00:50:35.551
AUDIENCE: Can you describe the
[INAUDIBLE] physical experiment

00:50:35.551 --> 00:50:37.429
that would show
that done, though?

00:50:37.429 --> 00:50:38.720
PROFESSOR: Oh yeah, absolutely.

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:42.700
So suppose I have a
little capacitor plate

00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:44.870
and there's a potential
difference across it

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:48.724
and a hole so a particle
could shoot threw it.

00:50:48.724 --> 00:50:50.890
I mean it doesn't have to
be an insanely small hole,

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:51.390
but a hole.

00:50:51.390 --> 00:50:53.232
So that if a particle
goes from here

00:50:53.232 --> 00:50:54.940
to the other side of
the capacitor plate,

00:50:54.940 --> 00:50:57.800
it will have accelerated across
the potential difference.

00:50:57.800 --> 00:51:00.740
So if you think about the
effective potential energy,

00:51:00.740 --> 00:51:02.490
the potential is
decreasing linearly.

00:51:02.490 --> 00:51:03.970
It's a constant electric field.

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:07.710
So over this short domain
between the capacitor plates,

00:51:07.710 --> 00:51:12.632
we have effectively a
linear potential energy.

00:51:12.632 --> 00:51:15.090
So I have a particle that I
send with very little momentum,

00:51:15.090 --> 00:51:16.180
but it carries some charge.

00:51:16.180 --> 00:51:17.410
It gets on capacitor
plates, and if it

00:51:17.410 --> 00:51:18.784
goes through the
capacitor plate,

00:51:18.784 --> 00:51:20.520
it ends with a lot
more energy relative

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:22.300
to the potential energy.

00:51:22.300 --> 00:51:23.220
That cool?

00:51:23.220 --> 00:51:25.400
So a little capacitor
plate with a hole in it

00:51:25.400 --> 00:51:28.100
is a beautiful example
of this system.

00:51:28.100 --> 00:51:28.600
Good?

00:51:28.600 --> 00:51:30.391
Now, making it infinitely
sharp, well, that

00:51:30.391 --> 00:51:31.500
would require-- you know.

00:51:31.500 --> 00:51:34.960
But making it very
sharp is no problem.

00:51:34.960 --> 00:51:37.920
So here's the inverse
of what we just did,

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:42.850
which is sending a
particle into a barrier.

00:51:42.850 --> 00:51:46.140
And so there you see it does
some quite awesome things.

00:51:46.140 --> 00:51:48.320
And I want to pause
it right here.

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:49.550
This is the energy band.

00:51:49.550 --> 00:51:51.510
So the green
represents-- it says

00:51:51.510 --> 00:51:54.489
that at any given energy
inside this green band,

00:51:54.489 --> 00:51:56.780
there's some contribution
from the corresponding energy

00:51:56.780 --> 00:51:59.730
eigenstate to our wave packet.

00:51:59.730 --> 00:52:02.200
There isn't any
contribution from states

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:04.680
up here where there's
no green, which

00:52:04.680 --> 00:52:06.732
means that all the
contributions come

00:52:06.732 --> 00:52:08.190
from energy
eigenstates with energy

00:52:08.190 --> 00:52:09.960
below the height of the barrier.

00:52:09.960 --> 00:52:14.080
None of them have enough
energy to cross the barrier.

00:52:14.080 --> 00:52:17.390
And what we see when we
send in our wave packet

00:52:17.390 --> 00:52:20.180
is some complicated mucking
around near the barrier,

00:52:20.180 --> 00:52:23.610
but in particular,
right there, there's

00:52:23.610 --> 00:52:26.100
a finite non-zero
probability that you're

00:52:26.100 --> 00:52:28.810
found in the classically
disallowed region.

00:52:28.810 --> 00:52:31.030
In the region where you
didn't have enough energy

00:52:31.030 --> 00:52:32.670
to get there.

00:52:32.670 --> 00:52:33.680
We see right there.

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:35.770
And meanwhile, there's
also a huge pile up here.

00:52:35.770 --> 00:52:36.620
This is a hard wall.

00:52:36.620 --> 00:52:38.320
Normally classically
from a hard wall,

00:52:38.320 --> 00:52:39.980
you roll along, you
hit the hard wall,

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:42.740
and you bounce off
instantaneously

00:52:42.740 --> 00:52:43.960
with the same velocity.

00:52:43.960 --> 00:52:46.750
But here what we're
saying is no, the wave

00:52:46.750 --> 00:52:48.940
doesn't just exactly
bounce off instantaneously.

00:52:48.940 --> 00:52:51.760
We get this complicated piling
up and the interference effect.

00:52:51.760 --> 00:52:54.590
So what's going on there?

00:52:54.590 --> 00:52:56.482
Well, it's precisely
an interference effect.

00:52:56.482 --> 00:52:57.690
So look at the wave function.

00:52:57.690 --> 00:52:59.900
The wave function is a much
easier thing to look at.

00:52:59.900 --> 00:53:02.610
So the red is the amplitude.

00:53:02.610 --> 00:53:03.930
The red is the real part.

00:53:03.930 --> 00:53:05.380
The black is the phase.

00:53:05.380 --> 00:53:08.060
So the real part is actually
behaving quite reasonably.

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:10.179
It looks like it's just
bouncing right off.

00:53:10.179 --> 00:53:12.470
But the physical thing is
the probability distribution.

00:53:12.470 --> 00:53:15.260
The probability distribution
has interference terms

00:53:15.260 --> 00:53:17.030
from the various
different contributions

00:53:17.030 --> 00:53:18.844
to the wave function.

00:53:18.844 --> 00:53:20.760
So at the collision those
interference effects

00:53:20.760 --> 00:53:22.062
are very important.

00:53:22.062 --> 00:53:23.770
And at late times
notice what's happened.

00:53:23.770 --> 00:53:25.700
At late times the
probability distribution

00:53:25.700 --> 00:53:28.979
all went right back off.

00:53:28.979 --> 00:53:31.020
So that's something else
we'd like to understand.

00:53:31.020 --> 00:53:34.522
Penetration into the
barrier from a classically

00:53:34.522 --> 00:53:35.480
disallowed wave packet.

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:35.980
Yup.

00:53:35.980 --> 00:53:40.124
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] the wave
packet is also expanding again?

00:53:40.124 --> 00:53:40.790
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:53:40.790 --> 00:53:41.831
The wave packet, exactly.

00:53:41.831 --> 00:53:44.102
So the wave packet is
always going to expand.

00:53:44.102 --> 00:53:46.310
And the reason is we're
taking our wave packet, which

00:53:46.310 --> 00:53:48.560
is a reasonably well-localized
approximately Gaussian wave

00:53:48.560 --> 00:53:49.100
packet.

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:51.340
So whatever else is
going on, while it's

00:53:51.340 --> 00:53:53.465
in the part of the potential
where the potential is

00:53:53.465 --> 00:53:56.030
constant, it's also
just dispersing.

00:53:56.030 --> 00:53:57.240
And so we can see that here.

00:53:57.240 --> 00:53:58.530
Let's make that more obvious.

00:53:58.530 --> 00:54:03.642
Let's make the initial wave
packet much more narrow.

00:54:03.642 --> 00:54:05.350
So if the wave packet's
much more narrow,

00:54:05.350 --> 00:54:06.724
we're going to
watch it disperse,

00:54:06.724 --> 00:54:09.950
and let's move the
wall over here.

00:54:09.950 --> 00:54:12.630
So long before it hits the wall
it's going to disperse, right?

00:54:12.630 --> 00:54:13.630
That's what we'd expect.

00:54:13.630 --> 00:54:15.380
And lo, watch it disperse.

00:54:15.380 --> 00:54:17.370
OK, now gets to the wall.

00:54:17.370 --> 00:54:22.275
And it's sort of a mess.

00:54:22.275 --> 00:54:24.400
Now, you see that there's
contributions to the wave

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:25.630
function over here,
there's support

00:54:25.630 --> 00:54:27.260
for the wave function
moving off to the right.

00:54:27.260 --> 00:54:29.634
But now notice that we have
support on energy eigenstates

00:54:29.634 --> 00:54:31.999
with energy above the barrier.

00:54:31.999 --> 00:54:34.040
So, indeed, it was possible
for some contribution

00:54:34.040 --> 00:54:34.998
to go off to the right.

00:54:38.430 --> 00:54:41.890
So one more of these guys.

00:54:41.890 --> 00:54:42.970
I guess two more.

00:54:42.970 --> 00:54:43.730
These are fun.

00:54:43.730 --> 00:54:47.320
So here's a hard wall.

00:54:47.320 --> 00:54:51.230
Let's make the-- So
here's a hard wall.

00:54:51.230 --> 00:54:53.870
But it's a finite width barrier.

00:54:53.870 --> 00:54:55.970
What happens?

00:54:55.970 --> 00:54:59.530
Well, this is basically the
same as what we just saw.

00:54:59.530 --> 00:55:01.230
We collide up against
that first wall,

00:55:01.230 --> 00:55:02.782
and since there's
an exponential fall

00:55:02.782 --> 00:55:04.565
off it doesn't really
matter that there's

00:55:04.565 --> 00:55:06.440
this other wall where
it falls down over here

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:08.856
because the wave function is
just exponentially suppressed

00:55:08.856 --> 00:55:11.070
in the classically
disallowed region.

00:55:11.070 --> 00:55:12.110
So let's see that again.

00:55:12.110 --> 00:55:13.990
It's always going to be
exponentially suppressed

00:55:13.990 --> 00:55:15.531
in the classically
disallowed region.

00:55:15.531 --> 00:55:18.930
As you see, there's that
big exponential suppression.

00:55:18.930 --> 00:55:20.720
So there's some
finite particle here,

00:55:20.720 --> 00:55:23.850
but you're really unlikely to
find it out here exponentially.

00:55:23.850 --> 00:55:28.320
On the other hand, if we
make the barrier-- so let's

00:55:28.320 --> 00:55:29.850
think about this barrier.

00:55:29.850 --> 00:55:34.440
Classically, this is just
as good as a thick barrier.

00:55:34.440 --> 00:55:36.770
You can't get passed this wall.

00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:40.210
But quantum mechanically
what happens?

00:55:40.210 --> 00:55:43.270
You go right through.

00:55:43.270 --> 00:55:43.770
Just--

00:55:43.770 --> 00:55:44.080
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:44.080 --> 00:55:45.038
PROFESSOR: --right on--

00:55:45.038 --> 00:55:51.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:51.720 --> 00:55:53.657
Yeah, uh-huh.

00:55:53.657 --> 00:55:54.240
Right through.

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:56.530
It barely even changes shape.

00:55:56.530 --> 00:55:57.830
It barely even changes shape.

00:55:57.830 --> 00:55:58.955
Just goes right on through.

00:55:58.955 --> 00:56:01.371
Now, there's some probability
that you go off to the left,

00:56:01.371 --> 00:56:02.372
that you bounce off.

00:56:02.372 --> 00:56:05.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:05.610 --> 00:56:06.430
I share your pain.

00:56:06.430 --> 00:56:09.210
I totally do.

00:56:09.210 --> 00:56:14.394
So I would like to do another
experiment which demonstrates

00:56:14.394 --> 00:56:17.060
the difference between classical
and quantum mechanical physics.

00:56:19.744 --> 00:56:20.244
Right.

00:56:20.244 --> 00:56:23.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:27.060
[APPLAUSE]

00:56:27.060 --> 00:56:28.610
So we have some
explaining to do.

00:56:28.610 --> 00:56:30.741
And this is going to turn
out to be-- surprisingly,

00:56:30.741 --> 00:56:32.240
this is not a hard
thing to explain.

00:56:32.240 --> 00:56:32.780
It's going to be real easy.

00:56:32.780 --> 00:56:34.155
Just like the
dispersion, this is

00:56:34.155 --> 00:56:37.060
going to be not a
hard thing to explain.

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:39.712
But the next one and this
is-- oh yeah, question.

00:56:39.712 --> 00:56:42.319
AUDIENCE: Does the height
of the spike matter?

00:56:42.319 --> 00:56:43.610
PROFESSOR: It does, absolutely.

00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:46.640
So the height of the spike and
the width of the spike matter.

00:56:46.640 --> 00:56:48.050
So let's make it a little wider.

00:56:48.050 --> 00:56:49.841
And what we're going
to see now is oh, it's

00:56:49.841 --> 00:56:54.045
a little less likely
to go through.

00:56:54.045 --> 00:56:55.570
If we make it just
a tiny bit wider

00:56:55.570 --> 00:56:57.695
we'll see that it's much
less likely to go through.

00:56:57.695 --> 00:56:59.320
We'll see much stronger
reflected wave.

00:56:59.320 --> 00:57:03.312
So both the height and width
are going to turn out to matter.

00:57:03.312 --> 00:57:05.770
So here you can see that there's
an appreciable reflection,

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:06.590
which there wasn't previously.

00:57:06.590 --> 00:57:08.173
Let's make it just
a little bit wider.

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:18.270
And now it's an awful lot
closer to half and half.

00:57:18.270 --> 00:57:20.020
See the bottom two lumps?

00:57:20.020 --> 00:57:22.325
Let's make it just
ever so slightly wider.

00:57:25.844 --> 00:57:27.260
And again, looking
down here we're

00:57:27.260 --> 00:57:28.613
going to have a transmitted
bit, but we're also

00:57:28.613 --> 00:57:29.550
going to have a
reflected-- now it

00:57:29.550 --> 00:57:32.010
looks like the reflected bit is
even a little bit larger maybe.

00:57:32.010 --> 00:57:34.551
And we can actually compute the
reflection transmission here.

00:57:34.551 --> 00:57:38.336
72% gets reflected and
28% get transmitted.

00:57:38.336 --> 00:57:40.960
I really strongly encourage you
to play with these simulations.

00:57:40.960 --> 00:57:42.584
They're both fun and
very illuminating.

00:57:42.584 --> 00:57:43.175
Yeah.

00:57:43.175 --> 00:57:45.905
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
just the higher it got,

00:57:45.905 --> 00:57:47.318
the less got transmitted?

00:57:47.318 --> 00:57:47.943
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:57:47.943 --> 00:57:50.046
AUDIENCE: So if this were
a delta function would

00:57:50.046 --> 00:57:50.990
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:53.350
PROFESSOR: Well,
what's the width?

00:57:53.350 --> 00:57:54.130
AUDIENCE: 0.

00:57:54.130 --> 00:57:57.290
PROFESSOR: So what
happens when we

00:57:57.290 --> 00:58:00.657
make the well less and
less-- or more and more thin?

00:58:00.657 --> 00:58:01.490
More, yeah, through.

00:58:01.490 --> 00:58:02.990
So we've got a competition
between the heights

00:58:02.990 --> 00:58:03.800
and the width.

00:58:03.800 --> 00:58:05.250
